
HawkEye G Application for Splunk
===============================

## Description ##

This application extracts fields from the syslog data stream generated by 
HawkEye G nodes. In addition, it implements dashboards that display 
the extracted data. These dashboards provide a situational overview of the
managed HawkEye G deployments.

#### Latest Version ####

* Splunk Version: 6.x
* App Version: 1.0
* Last Modified: Sept. 2015
* Authors: Hexis Cyber Solutions, Inc.

#### Version Compatibility ####

Splunk 6.x -- HawkEye G Application for Splunk v1.0

#### Support ####

For installation, support, or feedback, please contact support@hexiscyber.com.

## Quick Start Guide ##

### Dependencies ###

The HawkEye G Application for Splunk depends on the HawkEye G Logs Parser 
add-on. This add-on should be installed before installing this applicaiton.


### Install the app ###

- Unpack the tar ball into `$SPLUNK_HOME/etc/apps`
- Restart Splunk

### To get HawkEye G data into Splunk ###

IMPORTANT: When you configure the input port, you must set the sourcetype of 
the data to syslog and the index to hawkeyeg.  This can be done from the Web UI
or the CLI.  Then, configure the HawkEye G node to send syslog messages to
Splunk on the specified port.

#### From the Splunk Web UI ####

- Navigate to Manager -> Data Inputs -> TCP -> New
- Set the TCP port
- Set sourcetype: Manual
- Specify "syslog" as the sourcetype.
- Click on More settings
- Index: hawkeyeg

#### From the CLI via inputs.conf ####

- Edit `$SPLUNK_HOME/etc/apps/hgsplunk/local/inputs.conf` 

Example:

    [tcp://7514]
    index= hawkeyeg
    connection_host = ip
    sourcetype = syslog
    no_appending_timestamp = true

#### Configure HawkEye G ####

On the HawkEye G nodes monitored by this application, login as the "admin" user
to the HawkEye G Manager. Maneuver to "Settings->Event Forwarding" in order to 
configure the syslog server. Select "Add Server" and add the Splunk server's
details (IP address, TCP port, etc.). All subsequent syslog messages should
be forwarded to the newly added server.
